Data manipulation, exploration, and visualization made easy: the tidyverse packages

Welcome to the R workshop of the Idaho Chapter of The Wildlife Society meeting 2025! In this workshop, you will learn how to use functions in the tidyverse packages to manipulate, wrangle, and visualize data in an automated way. We are going to start by installing and loading the necessary packages. The functions we will use to work with data come from the tidyverse library and the data we will be working on come from the palmerpenguins library.

The code below installs the packages onto your computer. This is a one-time step that wont need to be repeated the next time you want to use these packages.

install.packages("tidyverse")
install.packages("palmerpenguins")

Now that the packages are installed, we can load them into our R session. This will need to be repeated every time you restart R and want to use these packages.

library(palmerpenguins)
library(tidyverse)
## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 4.3.3

The data comes as a tibble. A tibble is a tabular object similar to a data.frame, and it is the native form in which tables are displayed in the tidyverse. They are interoperable, and you can easily convert one into the other, but the advantage of tibbles is that they display in a more compact way in the console without us having to take extra steps to prevent the output to flood our screen.

Learning tidyverse functions

Lets get into the fun part and start learning how to manipulate data using the tidyverse.

Selecting columns

The function select allows us to choose only certain columns from a tibble. For instance, say that we only want to select columns that contain morphometrics information about individuals:

select(p, 
       "Species", 
       "Individual ID",
       "Culmen Length (mm)",
       "Culmen Depth (mm)",
       "Flipper Length (mm)",
       "Body Mass (g)")

Renaming columns

The column names in this dataset often contain spaces and special characters, like parentheses. This means I had to do a lot of typing in the previous piece of code, and I had to wrap column names in quotes. Tidy names contain no spaces and no special characters, and they allow us to refer to columns in tidyverse without having to put their names in quotes. Lets rename the columns and give them tidy names:

(p <- rename(p, 
            study_name = studyName,
            sample = "Sample Number",
            species = Species,
            region = Region,
            island = Island,
            age_class = Stage,
            ind_id = "Individual ID",
            clutch_comp = "Clutch Completion",
            date_egg = "Date Egg",
            culmen_length_mm = "Culmen Length (mm)",
            culmen_depth_mm = "Culmen Depth (mm)",
            flipper_length_mm = "Flipper Length (mm)",
            body_mass_g = "Body Mass (g)",
            sex = Sex,
            delta_15_n = "Delta 15 N (o/oo)",
            delta_13_c = "Delta 13 C (o/oo)",
            comments = Comments))

Concatenating multiple operations: the pipe

One of the best features of the tidyverse is the pipe, which looks like this: %>%. The pipe is an operator that allows us to concatenate multiple commands all in a row, without saving any intermediate objects. The output of the previous command becomes the input of the next. You can read the pipe as then. For example, in the following code, we take our penguin data.frame, then we turn it into a tibble, then we rename the columns, then we select the columns of interest:

(morph <- p_df %>%
  as_tibble() %>% 
  rename(study_name = studyName,
         sample = "Sample Number",
         species = Species,
         region = Region,
         island = Island,
         age_class = Stage,
         ind_id = "Individual ID",
         clutch_comp = "Clutch Completion",
         date_egg = "Date Egg",
         culmen_length_mm = "Culmen Length (mm)",
         culmen_depth_mm = "Culmen Depth (mm)",
         flipper_length_mm = "Flipper Length (mm)",
         body_mass_g = "Body Mass (g)",
         sex = Sex,
         delta_15_n = "Delta 15 N (o/oo)",
         delta_13_c = "Delta 13 C (o/oo)",
         comments = Comments) %>% 
  select(sample,
         ind_id,
         species,
         sex,
         age_class,
         culmen_length_mm,
         culmen_depth_mm,
         flipper_length_mm, 
         body_mass_g))
## # A tibble: 344  9

Dropping columns

The select function can also be used to drop columns, rather than specifying the ones we want to keep. We place a minus sign in front of the columns we want to get rid of:

(morph <- morph %>% 
  select(-sample))

Finding unique combinations

Say that we want to find all the unique combinations of individual ID, species, and sex that occur in the data. We can combine the select function with the distinct function, to return all unique combinations of the specified columns:

(ind_info <- p %>% 
  # Columns we want to find unique combinations of
  select(ind_id, species, sex) %>% 
  distinct())
## # A tibble: 298  3

Extracting single columns as vectors

Now, lets say that we want to check how many different individual IDs exist in the data. In this case, rather than a combination of columns, we only want to find unique values in one column. The function distinct works on a tibble, while the function unique (which is not a tidyverse function, but a base R function), wants a vector as input. For this reason, using select before unique is not going to work. The function we want to use instead is pull. This function returns a single column as a vector. For instance, lets see how many unique individual IDs exist in the data:

p %>% 
  pull(ind_id) %>% 
  unique()

There are 190 unique IDs. However, the number of unique combinations of ID, species, and sex has more rows than that (298). This means there are repeated IDs in the data! What is going on?

Filtering data

Lets take a look, for instance, at the ID N11A1. We can use the function filter to subset the rows that have that ID:

ind_info %>% 
  filter(ind_id == "N11A1")
## # A tibble: 2  3
##   ind_id species                             sex   
##   <chr>  <chr>                               <chr> 
## 1 N11A1  Adelie Penguin (Pygoscelis adeliae) FEMALE
## 2 N11A1  Gentoo penguin (Pygoscelis papua)   FEMALE

It looks like this same ID was assigned to two individuals of different species. How can we find all the individual IDs that are repeated in the data?

Grouping and doing operations by group

To find out which IDs are repeated, we can count the number of rows each individual ID appears in. We can do that by grouping rows by individual IDs and then counting the number of rows in each group:

ind_info %>% 
  group_by(ind_id) %>% 
  tally()
## # A tibble: 190  2
##    ind_id     n
##    <chr>  <int>
##  1 N100A1     1
##  2 N100A2     1
##  3 N10A1      1
##  4 N10A2      1
##  5 N11A1      2
##  6 N11A2      2
##  7 N12A1      2
##  8 N12A2      2
##  9 N13A1      2
## 10 N13A2      2
## #  180 more rows

Sorting results

If we want to know how many times, at most, IDs are repeated, we can sort the results of the counts by group:

ind_info %>% 
  group_by(ind_id) %>% 
  tally() %>% 
  arrange(n)
## # A tibble: 190  2
##    ind_id     n
##    <chr>  <int>
##  1 N100A1     1
##  2 N100A2     1
##  3 N10A1      1
##  4 N10A2      1
##  5 N14A1      1
##  6 N14A2      1
##  7 N15A1      1
##  8 N15A2      1
##  9 N16A1      1
## 10 N16A2      1
## #  180 more rows

That didnt quite work it sorted results in ascending order, so all we were able to see at a glance is that the IDs with the fewest repetitions are only used once. But what we want to do is look at the IDs with the most repetitions and find out how many times they were used. We can reverse the order:

ind_info %>% 
  group_by(ind_id) %>% 
  tally() %>% 
  arrange(desc(n))
## # A tibble: 190  2
##    ind_id     n
##    <chr>  <int>
##  1 N24A1      3
##  2 N24A2      3
##  3 N29A1      3
##  4 N29A2      3
##  5 N36A1      3
##  6 N38A2      3
##  7 N67A1      3
##  8 N67A2      3
##  9 N8A1       3
## 10 N8A2       3
## #  180 more rows

It turns out that, at most, the same ID was reused three times. Here is how to find all the IDs that were used more than once:

ind_info %>% 
  group_by(ind_id) %>% 
  tally() %>% 
  filter(n > 1)
## # A tibble: 98  2
##    ind_id     n

##  8 N17A2      2
##  9 N18A1      2
## 10 N18A2      2
## #  88 more rows

Creating new columns

Having a column that uniquely identifies each individual is very useful, so were going to create a new column that contains a new individual ID, with no repetitions. For example, we can create a column with the prefix ID followed by an incremental number:

(ind_info <- ind_info %>% 
  mutate(new_id = paste0("ID", 1:nrow(.))))

Conditional value assignment

Alternatively, if we wanted something more sophisticated and we did not want to lose the original ID that was assigned to each individual, we can append to it the initial of the species and the initial of the sex. Each combination of original ID, species, and sex will now be uniquely identifiable. To do this, we use the function mutate that we saw above and we combine it with the function case_when, which performs conditional value assignment. We make a series of logical statements and specify the value that should be in the new column depending on whether those statements are true:

(ind_info <- ind_info %>% 
  mutate(species_initial = case_when(
    species == "Adelie Penguin (Pygoscelis adeliae)" ~ "A",
    species == "Gentoo penguin (Pygoscelis papua)" ~ "G",
    species == "Chinstrap penguin (Pygoscelis antarctica)" ~ "C"
  ),
  sex_initial = case_when(
    sex == "MALE" ~ "M",
    sex == "FEMALE" ~ "F",
    is.na(sex) ~ "U"
  )) %>% 
  mutate(new_id = paste(ind_id, species_initial, sex_initial, sep = "_")) %>% 
  select(-species_initial, -sex_initial))
## # A tibble: 298  4
##    ind_id species                             sex    new_id  
##    <chr>  <chr>                               <chr>  <chr>   
##  1 N1A1   Adelie Penguin (Pygoscelis adeliae) MALE   N1A1_A_M
##  2 N1A2   Adelie Penguin (Pygoscelis adeliae) FEMALE N1A2_A_F
##  3 N2A1   Adelie Penguin (Pygoscelis adeliae) FEMALE N2A1_A_F
##  4 N2A2   Adelie Penguin (Pygoscelis adeliae) <NA>   N2A2_A_U
##  5 N3A1   Adelie Penguin (Pygoscelis adeliae) FEMALE N3A1_A_F
##  6 N3A2   Adelie Penguin (Pygoscelis adeliae) MALE   N3A2_A_M
##  7 N4A1   Adelie Penguin (Pygoscelis adeliae) FEMALE N4A1_A_F
##  8 N4A2   Adelie Penguin (Pygoscelis adeliae) MALE   N4A2_A_M

## 10 N5A2   Adelie Penguin (Pygoscelis adeliae) <NA>   N5A2_A_U

Lets check that now there are as many new IDs as there are rows in the individual information table:

length(unique(ind_info$new_id)) == nrow(ind_info)

Limiting results and subsetting rows by position

It is useful to be able to look at just a subset of the rows. For example, we might just want to see the first row of a dataset; we might just want to see the first three; we might want to see a specific subset of non-consecutive rows; or we might want to see the first row for each group (e.g., for each species, or for each combination of species and sex). The slice funciton can do all of those things:

Data visualization with ggplot2

The ggplot2 package allows us to produce beautiful data visualizations, even quite complex ones in an automated and simple way.

The logic of ggplot follows the Grammar of Graphics framework, which was first introduced in a book by Leland Wilkinson. This framework concisely describes the different components of a graphic. At a minimum, a plot is composed of data, aesthetics, and geometries:

  • Data: this is the data that are represented on a plot;
  • Aesthetics: these are the variables that are represented on the plot (e.g., what goes on the axes, or what is encoded with different symbols and colors);
  • Geometries: these are the actual symbols that appear on the plot (points, lines, etc.)

On top of these fundamental components, there can be additional elements for customization. The plot is initialized using the ggplot function, and all elements get added as layers connected by + signs.

Boxplot of body mass by species

Lets make a boxplot of penguin body mass by species. Here, our data is the penguin dataset. Our aesthetics include the variable on the x axis (the species), the variable on the y axis (the body mass), and the color of our boxplots (which will be in different colors depending on the species). The geometries on the plot will be the boxplots and the original data points (jittered a little bit so that they are not all on top of each other). Since the species names are already on the x axis, the legend is redundant and we can remove it. We complete the plot with a clean theme, nice axis labels, and a nice color palette.

ggplot(p, aes(y = body_mass_g, x = species, color = species)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.3) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = "", y = "Body mass (g)", color = "Species") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Accent")

Density plot of flipper length by species

Lets make a density plot of penguin flipper length by species. Again, our data is the penguin dataset. The aesthetics include the variable on the x axis (the flipper length) and the variable that we will use to assign a fill color to each density curve (the species). Because this is a density plot, the variable on the y axis will be the density, which is calculated automatically by geom_density and we do not need to specify that in the aesthetics. We then add our geometry (the density curves). We complete the plot with a clean theme, nice axis labels, and a nice color palette, and we customize the position of the legend on the plot.

ggplot(p, aes(x = flipper_length_mm, fill = species)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5) + 
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = "Flipper length (mm)", y = "Density", fill = "Species") + 
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Accent")

Scatterplot of isotopic values by species and island

Lets make a scatterplot of isotopic values (carbon and nitrogen) for penguins by species and island. Here, the aesthetics will be the two isotope variables on the x and y axes, and the species as the color variable. Our geometries will be points, and we will have a different panel for each island. We complete the plot with a clean theme, nice axis labels, and a color palette.

ggplot(p, aes(x = delta_13_c, y = delta_15_n, color = species)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~ island) +
  labs(x = "Delta 13C", y = "Delta 15N", color = "Species") +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Accent")

Scatterplot of culmen depth and length by body mass and species

Presumably, larger penguins will simultaneously have longer limbs and higher body mass. Lets see if this holds true by making a scatterplot of culmen depth and length by body mass and species. Here, our x and y aesthetics will be the culmen length and depth, respectively. The color aesthetic will be the species. We can add an additional aesthetic by making the size of the points vary with the value of body mass. We complete the plot with a clean theme, nice axis labels, and a nice color palette. Notice that in this case, I changed the order in which I specified the customization options, because it does not matter which order they get added in.

ggplot(p, aes(x = culmen_length_mm, y = culmen_depth_mm, 
              color = species, size = body_mass_g)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Accent") +
  labs(x = "Culmen length (mm)", y = "Culmen depth (mm)",
       color = "Species", size = "Body mass (g)") +
  theme_bw()

Adding regression lines with confidence intervals

A common scenario is wanting to create a plot of our data overlaid to the output of a model, for instance, a linear regression. To do that, we have to take a few extra steps before we can create the plot. First, we need to run a regression model and generate predictions from it.

mod <- lm(culmen_depth_mm ~ culmen_length_mm * species, data = p)

new_data <- expand.grid(species = factor(unique(p$species)),
            culmen_length_mm = seq(min(p$culmen_length_mm, na.rm = TRUE),
                                   max(p$culmen_length_mm, na.rm = TRUE),
                                   length.out = 100))

preds <- predict(mod, newdata = new_data, se.fit = TRUE)

res <- new_data %>% 
  mutate(culmen_depth_mm = preds$fit,
         culmen_depth_lwr_ci = preds$fit - preds$se.fit * 1.96,
         culmen_depth_upr_ci = preds$fit + preds$se.fit * 1.96)

Now we are ready to plot. We can take the code from the previous plot and include a ribbon for the confidence intervals and a line for the mean prediction in addition to the points for the raw data. Because we want the size aesthetic to only apply to the points, we will move it from the general ggplot function into the appropriate layer. Note that, in this plot, we are combining two datasets: the raw penguin data (for the points) and the predictions table (for the line and ribbon). We can specify different datasets in different layers. The names of the x and y variables, as well as the name of the color variable, are the same in both data frames, so we can define those aesthetics in the main ggplot layer. For the ribbon layer, we will need to add three more aesthetics: the minimum y value at which the ribbon should start, the maximum y value at which it should end, and the color we want the inside of the ribbon to be. We can add some transparency to make sure we can still see the line on top of it. In this case, we have both a color and a fill variable for different components of the plot, so we want to specify the same palette for both. Notice that, in this case, it was important to add the layers in the right order because we needed the line to be on top of the ribbon, which in turn is on top of the points, for everything to be visible. We complete the plot with a clean theme and nice axis labels.

ggplot(p, aes(x = culmen_length_mm, y = culmen_depth_mm, color = species)) +
  geom_point(aes(size = body_mass_g)) +
  geom_ribbon(data = res, 
              mapping = aes(ymin = culmen_depth_lwr_ci,
                            ymax = culmen_depth_upr_ci,
                            fill = species),
              alpha = 0.3) +
  geom_line(data = res) +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Accent") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Accent") +
  labs(x = "Culmen length (mm)", y = "Culmen depth (mm)",
       color = "Species", fill = "Species", size = "Body mass (g)") +
  theme_bw()

Scatterplot of flipper and culmen length by body mass and sex (Adelie only)

We can seamlessly combine the tidyverse syntax we learned in the first part of the workshop with ggplot2 functions. Lets make an example of that by creating a scatterplot of flipper and culmen length by body mass and sex for Adelie penguins only. Instead of filtering Adelie penguins and creating a separate object for that subset of data, we can directly pipe our filtered dataset into the ggplot function, and it will be used as the input data. We will also get rid of individuals for which the sex was not recorded. Then, we specify our aesthetics: culmen and flipper length go on the x and y axes, respectively, and the points will be colored depending on the value of body mass. Notice that this is the first time we use a continuous color palette. We separate sexes into two different panels. We increase the size of the points. We complete the plot with a clean theme and nice axis labels.

p %>% 
  filter(grepl("Adelie", species) &
           !is.na(sex)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = culmen_length_mm, y = flipper_length_mm, 
              color = body_mass_g)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  facet_wrap(~ sex) +
  scale_color_viridis_c() +
  labs(x = "Culmen length (mm)", y = "Flipper length (mm)",
       color = "Body mass (g)") +
  theme_bw()
